text:
when i die i want to be dressed in black
black because it was the darkness that comforted me in my time of pain and self destruction 
darkness was the soft music playing in my head while i laid down and just thought about dying 
black because all i know is how to be comfortable in the dark 
darkness because i felt whole in it 
i wasnâ€™t broken in the dark 
in darkness you see nothing 
i didnâ€™t see myself in pieces
i liked not seeing anything 
it put peace in my soul
in those dark lonely nights 
i trained myself how do better or worse by myself. ***
-deniseâ›ˆ *my poem*

text:
a little while ago a guy i was talking to had claimed to be very interested in me and that i was worth fighting for. i shared with him this part of myself (in a condensed version) and he got so angry. he said he couldn't imagine what else i was 'hiding'. he said he couldn't believe i could call myself a woman of god and not share that with him within the first week or so of talking. 
i wasn't even able to defend myself because he wouldn't reply to my messages. 5 days later he posted that he was in a relationship with someone else and then blocked me. i was really hurt and felt stifled. 
i have carried so much guilt, and shame in my life. i have seen myself as damaged goods. i've been learning to love myself the way jesus loves me. but the comments this guy made were like pouring salt in my wounds
i am selective about sharing this part of myself. i don't want people to see me differently or feeling sorry for me. i also feel like it isn't something that everyone needs to know and i don't think that's unreasonable. i'm sharing it here because as i've been hurting over this and praying yahweh told me i needed to share this on my instagram. i'm kinda nervous. 
a little over 6 years ago i took a pregnancy test and it was positive.
went to the doctor and the blood test confirmed that i was pregnant. 
i was devastated. my whole world had been turned upside down. i wanted to die. 
i had become pregnant when someone forced himself on me. due to being sexually abused earlier in my life the moment he crossed that line i shut down. i didn't fight back or say no or anything because i had dissociated and left my body. it didn't look like a conventional rape - like you'd see on tv or whatever so it took me weeks to even entertain the idea that i had been taken advantage of (to be honest it's still a struggle).
i ended up booking an abortion. 2 days before i had gone home to see my parents so they could say goodbye to the little boy who would have been their first grandchild. my parents convinced me not to go through with it. i am so grateful for their support in that. ...continued in comments

text:
from trump to #metoo, publishing made headlines in 2018 | trending
#
fear: bob woodward, a brand name for inside white house politics, seemed to withdraw during the obama years. his two works on obama, "the price of politics" and "the last of the president's men," made little impact compared to such early blockbusters as the watergate-era "all the president's men." and his only book during obama's second term was a return to the nixon years: "the last of the president's men," about alexander butterfield, the white house aide who revealed to the world that nixon had a taping system in the oval office. but trump is a singular muse for political writers and with "fear: inside the trump white house," woodward was fully back in the present. "fear," woodward's hottest seller in years, read like a more sober version of "fire and fury," another tale of an uncontrollable chief executive and a staff that tries both to contain and encourage him. trump's verdict: "the woodward book is a joke."Â (ap photo/pablo martinez monsivais, file) article source...

text:
special announcement! 
salishan resort | february 8-10, 2019
www.salishan.com

we will be presenting our very first retreat this february! 
we are so excited to announce that the location of this retreat will be 
at salishan resort, a luxury destination resort on the oregon coast. 
this woodsy lodge is secluded between siletz bay and pacific ocean views, 
and captures the pioneering spirit and rugged style of the pacific northwest. 
this property promotes exploration, nature, wellness, and self development. 
we are thrilled to make salishan the home of our first retreat! 
@her_soulstory will be guiding a retreat called: â€œcreating the new story of our lives.â€ join us for a weekend of relaxation, wilderness, spa, and personal growth. 
together, we will create the new story of our lives, and dive deep into the personal work around the stories we have been saying to ourselves that are simply untrue. we will learn how to let go of the stories that no longer serve us, and together we will create new ones.

more details coming soon! 
www.hersoulstory.com

text:
suicide is the biggest killer of men under 35. 
men report significantly lower life satisfaction than women. men make up 76% of all suicides. men make up 
95% of the prison population. men make up 73% of all adults who go missing and men make up 87% of rough sleepers.
.
.
.

@lprh_ delves into masculinity in 2018, what's toxicity, and how does it impact the lives of men, and the lives of all.
.
.

link in bio, thanks to the incredibly talented @gabriellamussurakis for her beautiful artwork on this piece.

#mentalhealth #toxicmasculinity #metoo #masculinity #gender #race #identity

text: a child advocacy center serves children in the community who have been the victim of a crime. here you will find multi- disciplinary teams which are comprised of law enforcement personnel, therapists, forensic interviewers, medical personnel, and social workers. these centers are child friendly; reduces the trauma a child experiences when they are subjected to countless interviews by various teams, and the centers also take away the fear or anxiety associated with a child being taken into a police station. if your child has been the victim of a crime and you are not immediately connected to a child advocacy center after a police report is filed, ask the investigating officer to help you get connected. child advocacy centers are not available in every city, but we definitely encourage you to inquire. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

why? thanks for asking.
âœ¨ she defied beauty standards by embracing the growth of facial hair on her face, and rejecting the traditional societal view of what it meant to be feminine.
âœ¨ she was a bisexual babe. while she married a man, she still had many lovers of the same sex, including the american painter, georgia o'keeffe.
âœ¨ she survived a traumatic bus incident that should have killed her, which ruined her spine, created massive amounts of pain in her hips and knees, and she translated her pain into her art.
âœ¨ she drew inspiration from herself, and was her own muse. she knew herself more than she knew anyone else, and found beauty in the self reflection her art required.
so.. yeah. itâ€™s pretty hard not to love kahlo.
.
.

dame joan collins has slammed political correctness calling the world â€œpc mad.â€ she expressed her outrage at people taking offence to sir tom jones and cerys mathews christmas song collaboration â€œitâ€™s cold outside.â€ the song was taken off of a radio station in cleveland following complains that itâ€™s â€˜inappropriateâ€™ and goes against the me too movement. listeners described the lyrics as being â€œmanipulative and wrongâ€ as tom jones is strongly trying to convince cerys to stay inside with him when she repeatedly says she wants to leave throughout the song. dame joan collins was angered by this argument as well as political correctness in general. she said during her interview on good morning britain, â€œwhatâ€™s going to happen to seduction, is it not going to be allowed anymore? i mean, is someone going to have to ask permission to the parents before they can kiss a girl? itâ€™s absolutely becoming out of control and seems to have happened in the last two years, itâ€™s being exacerbated and becoming worse and worse. baby, itâ€™s cold outside is one of the sweetest songs, really gentle and kind and funny, and how dare they? the worldâ€™s gone nuts! we canâ€™t joke about anything any more. grew up going to variety theatres because my father was an agent and put on shows, so i saw comedians of all ilks and all nationalities making jokes about other nationalities and using these outrageous metaphors for them. you canâ€™t do that, you canâ€™t say anything, you canâ€™t say somebody has frizzy hair, you canâ€™t say theyâ€™re short, the only thing you can do is make jokes about age. but try to say anything about anybody whoâ€™s a little bit overweight or not exactly very tall, and you get banned for life.â€ sir tom jones and cerys matthews song isnâ€™t the only old christmas hit to recently come under fire. this year â€˜fairytale of new yorkâ€™ by the pogues and kirsty maccoll was scrutinised for having the word â€œfaggotâ€ in it and was labelled a homophobic song, however some argued that the word in ireland is defined as a person who is lazy as opposed to the american derogatory term for being gay.

https://fundly.com/hospitality-industry-standing-with-survivors

recently, iâ€™ve had more people than usual reaching out to me - asking for advice on emerging from toxic situations. maybe itâ€™s the holidays, maybe itâ€™s the end of the year and maybe itâ€™s just because we are in a special time in history where we are using our voices, breaking out from the mold, and experiencing freedom in its many forms. on the other hand, because of unhappiness and people not living out their destinies, not connecting with their purpose, reports of suicide, people harming themselves, and sadness seem to be hitting us from every side. if you or anyone you know is struggling in a toxic situation and truly want to get out and live the life you were destined to live, within the purpose that you were created for, please reach out to me. i am here for you and iâ€™m here for your journey.

text:
mgtow 101: mimicking melanin - real jews don't need man made products for protection

they dance around in black face to mock you, then wear black face so they can survive in the sun, the irony.

this is how the tanning process stimulates the production of melanin and makes it darker:

the uvb-component in sunlight (or from the lamps in a tanning bed) stimulates the melanocytes-cells in the outer skin-layer (epidermis) to produce more melanin.

the uva-component in sunlight (or from the lamps in a tanning bed) oxidizes the new and also the already existing melanin to a darker color.

the now darkened melanin forms a barrier around the cells in the body and uses its black or dark brown color to diffuse additional uvb-rays that could be harmful. the brown melanin molecules also move towards the very surface of the skin in order to form an additional barrier towards over-exposure from uv-light.

research has linked exposure to the sun's ultraviolet rays to skin cancer, premature wrinkles, and other skin problems. while protective clothing such as hats, pants, and long sleeve shirts are the most effective blocks against these damaging rays,Â sun-screenÂ lotions also provide remarkable protection for the skin.

the light emitted by the sun consists of three frequency bands of radiation: infrared, visible, and ultraviolet. of the three, only the ultraviolet is harmful to most humans. ultraviolet (uv) radiation is further divided into three categories: uva, uvb, and uvc. uva radiation penetrates the skin without burning the surface layers. these rays can penetrate to a depth of 0.04 inches (1.0 mm) and cause damage to cell membranes and the immune system. uva radiation has been linked to skin cancers and premature aging and wrinkling of the skin. uvb radiation is responsible for the painful, red burn people get after prolonged exposure to the sun. uvb rays also cause skin cancer and can damage the cornea and lens of the eye. the third category, uvc radiation, is generally absorbed by the earth's atmosphere and is not considered harmful. sunscreen lotions that provide protection against both uva and uvb radiation are known as having a broad spectrum of protection.

the uva-component in sunlight (or from the lamps in a tanning bed) oxidizes the new and also the already existing melanin to a darker color.

the now darkened melanin forms a barrier around the cells in the body and uses its black or dark brown color to diffuse additional uvb-rays that could be harmful. the brown melanin molecules also move towards the very surface of the skin in order to form an additional barrier towards over-exposure from uv-light.

research has linked exposure to the sun's ultraviolet rays to skin cancer, premature wrinkles, and other skin problems. while protective clothing such as hats, pants, and long sleeve shis are the most effective blocks against these damaging rays,Â sun-screenÂ lotions also provide remarkable protection for the skin.

the light emitted by the sun consists of three frequency bands of radiation: infrared, visible, and ultraviolet. of the three, only the ultraviolet is harmful to most humans. ultraviolet (uv) radiation is fuher divided into three categories: uva, uvb, and uvc. uva radiation penetrates the skin without burning the surface layers. these rays can penetrate to a depth of 0.04 inches (1.0 mm) and cause damage to cell membranes and the immune system. uva radiation has been linked to skin cancers and premature aging and wrinkling of the skin. uvb radiation is responsible for the painful, red burn people get after prolonged exposure to the sun. uvb rays also cause skin cancer and can damage the cornea and lens of the eye. the third category, uvc radiation, is generally absorbed by the eah's atmosphere and is not considered harmful. sunscreen lotions that provide protection against both uva and uvb radiation are known as having a broad spectrum of protection.

text: this is unrelated to what i usually post but i felt the need to make a statement here too. i've first heard of what yael could *possibly* go through a month ago, but i never realized it was bad to this extent. what she had gone through at the age of 25, working with someone she thought was her hero, but ended up being a predator in disguise... i can't even fathom what was going through her mind while she was physically and mentally going through harassment she couldn't fight off as she should have. the consequences she had to suffer, the fear, the pain, especially during her pregnancy and later with a newborn... i take my hat off to her. she's put her entire career and future possibilities related to working in her home state on the line. she did it all to warn people about a well known and sadly respected man who is a predator in disguise. who has used and hurt women before. and now she has to suffer for the despicable actions he did towards her when he was well over twice her age. in what kind of a crappy world do we live in where survivors have to carry the burden of the perpetrators? makes my stomach twist and be fearful of my own future. #metoo #yaelstone

text:
itâ€™s been a week since my abuser was arrested. the justice system has held him accountable for his actions but will he ever hold himself accountable? will he change the way he treats his partners? that i will never know. my hope is that no one else will have to suffer the way i did. and i truly mean suffer, physically and emotionally.

the last night my abuser and i were together we went to the movie a star is born. after the movie, when we got into the car he began screaming at me for not saying thank you when someone held the door open for me. after about 10 minutes of trying to drive while listening to him scream at me like a child, fearing he might hit me, or grab the wheel, i looked at him and i said to him calmly, â€œhow does it make you feel to talk to me like that? does it feel good? do you feel better, like a real man now?â€ stunned, he told me he wasnâ€™t happy and didnâ€™t want to be in this relationship anymore. me too i said as i breathed a sigh of relief. i dropped him off at his apartment and never saw him again.
having the strength that night to speak up for the first time, gave me momentum. he continued to harass me afterward, and after many attempts of asking him not to contact me, i went to the police. to speak up for myself, to be brave, to use my voice. 
i will always think it was fate that we went to see a star is born that night. and i will always be grateful for the message i took away from that night. â€œall youâ€™ve got is you, and what you have to say to peopleâ€ well, i survived, i have a voice, and itâ€™s only getting louder. i hope my story inspires others. you can get out, and you can protect yourself! you can stand up for yourself & for womenâ€™s rights!

while rape and sexual assault remain taboos in our society,the aftermath of an attack is far worse than the attack itself, and no one prepares you or talks about what comes after. when you hear the word ptsd (post traumatic stress disorder) you usually think of warfare, right? someone whoâ€™s experienced horrific things, things so terrible that it has literally altered the personâ€™s ability to cope in everyday life.
people donâ€™t tell you that after the attack you feel worthless and tainted, that your rapist takes away your privacy, safety, and confidence after they discard you.people donâ€™t tell you that you will lose faith in humanity, that youâ€™ll struggle letting anyone close to you and that something as genuine and sincere as a hug will make you recoil in fear. being a survivor of sexual assault is a very dark and lonely place.

text:
"when i look at myself i still see that punk kid, who thought she could travel the world and nothing & no one would stop her. "

she's still there,  she's just..adapting.. evolving.. moving forward.

feels good to be getting back to myself again.  even though you see a woman, with her life growing all around her,  you don't see her life she hides, inside her mind & heart.  there is defeats,  accomplishments,  sorrow,  devastation,  the list goes on. she will hold steady,  until one by one she conquers them all.  remember to stay kind, but true to yourself. embrace the "let go" of life! embrace your identity & don't take this social media shit so seriously.  namaste~ .
.
.

text:
find someone who will cry with you.
.
according to the google, holding space for someone means listening without judgment, giving your ears/heart without any expectation in return, practicing empathy and compassion.
.
this weekend i saw a post with #datingadvice - specifically about the kind of men that women should be attracted to. the qualities that they described: someone that would be strong for you. someone who could be your rock. someone to protect you.
.
whatâ€™s wrong with this? first, it perpetuates a culture where us gals are depicted as being emotional (in a derogatory sense) and excludes men (or masculine figures) from being sensitive, nurturing, etc. or displaying emotions that could be construed as â€˜weakâ€™.
.
ladies, let me tell you a few things society wonâ€™t: you are strong. you are immovable. you are capable. your intuition and feeling are a source of great strength.
.
speaking from my perspective, expecting male figures to be strong and protective not only undermines our own capabilities as a woman, but also excludes men from expressing the emotions they feel.
.
while everyoneâ€™s experience/expectations on relationships (romantic or not) is different, after being with my husband for ~10 years iâ€™d like to say that we should all want to be with someone who will cry with us. to hold space for us when weâ€™re grieving, hurt, or scared. to remind us that we are strong. to support us in finding our own voice and seeking healing in the way our intuitions lead.
.
my husband has been there just to cry with me. heâ€™s cried with me when iâ€™ve remembered suppressed #trauma from my childhood. heâ€™s cried with me through an #autoimmune diagnosis. heâ€™s cried with me when iâ€™ve stood up and said #metoo
.
i donâ€™t need someone to be strong for me. iâ€™m already strong. but i do appreciate having a partner/friend who can come along side me to hold space.
.

.
.

#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

nypd detective nicholas digaudio (right), escorts harvey weinstein into court in new york city on may 25. mark lennihan/ap hide caption toggle caption mark lennihan/ap nypd detective nicholas digaudio (right), escorts harvey weinstein into court in new york city on may 25. mark lennihan/ap harvey weinstein's arrest in may marked a watershed moment for the #metoo movement. weinstein was charged with sexually assaulting three women after dozens of women came forward to accuse the movie mogul of rape and sexual misconduct. but six months after his dramatic arrest, the criminal case against weinstein hasn't turned out to be the slam dunk that many people expected. one of the assault charges against weinstein has been dropped. and the rest of the case may be in jeopardy, too. police and prosecutors are blaming each other for undermining the case. and his defense lawyers are using that finger-pointing to their advantage. weinstein has always denied sexually assaulting anyone; he says the encounters were consensual. and this week, his lawyers will be in court trying to get the entire criminal case against him thrown out. the detective harvey weinstein turned himself in to police in lower manhattan in may. it was a chaotic scene.â€¦

text:
a must read per #malcolmgladwell ğŸ™ƒ and now #metoo ğŸ˜œ
the premise of this book is this quote by f. scott fitzgerald - "the test of first rate intelligence is the ability to hold two opposing ideas in mind at the same time and still retain the ability to function" 
the #book highlights the fact that the world we live in is #multidimensional and our default internal factory setting of sticking to certain #mentalmodels as true and be trapped in #confirmationbias such that we exclude all other models of #reality that exist is such a limiting factor for our #experience and #exploration .. #rogermartin  gives a #framework to cultivate an #opposablemind and myriad of real life business examples to bring home this amazing ability :)
-------------------------------
some great quotes :
* integrative thinkers don't flinch from considering multidirectional and nonlinear causal relationships
* fundamentally the conventional #thinker prefers to accept the world as it is. the integrative thinker welcomes the challenge of shaping the world for the better * reality is merely an illusion, albeit a very persistent one
* one factory preset of the human mind is a tendency to assume that our models of reality are identical to reality itself * our first impulse is to determine which one represents reality and which one is unreal and wrong, and then we campaign against the idea we reject * our mental models are hypotheses rather than the truth
* specialists aren't optimally suited to solve the biggest problems businesses face

text:
watching my dog run has reminded me how easily i lose focus and forget what was an initial goal of whatever project i have stared. my mind has a tendency to spin with a speed of thousands thoughts per hour, with each following thought trying to convince me that a previous thought is worthless. rational part of my brain knows that it is anxiety talk, but it is way easier to believe that anxious rant rather than facts. .
one this that helps to shut that toxic anxiety talk is to stay centered. pets do that for me. knowing that there is someone who depends on you, loves you unconditionally no matter what you think about yourself and runs towards you as if they are afraid to miss a single moment with you - that helps me to keep on and move forwards, one cuddle at a time. .
how do you cope with your toxic thoughts?

text:
hi my name is margaret wroblewski (@margaretwroblewski) and i started a photojournalism project called underground. it is a project that covers stories of sexual assault within public spaces. 
it has been published by @washingtonpost, @bbcnews, @npr, wamu, and @nbcnews. 
it all started on a cold night in february as i was heading home from my video class. an older man got on the train with a walker. he sat down across from me and began masturbating. he looked straight at me, his stare locked in on my face. i was traumatized, angry, and sad all at once. he used my body as an object to gratify himself. i am a graduate student at george washington university, and every single night i take the metro home for my 90-minute commute. 
a commute that should be spent listening to music, reading, or grumbling over train delays. but those luxuries have been stripped away and replaced with unsettling fear. since my first encounter, i have been subjected to harassment on the metro three more times.Â  i believe we can not be passive when it comes to sexual harassment - we have to make it stop. 
so, i decided to use my photography talents to inspire a movement. i decided to turn on my camera and share my story. it turns out i am not alone. what started out as a personal trauma has transformed into a national story.

please follow the project atÂ @undergroundseriesÂ or submit a story if you have one as well. it is time for sexual harassment to be recognized, rejected, and prevented. sexual harassment in unacceptable. 
everyone should feel safe on public transit. join me if you think so too. #unitedinwomanhood

text: "on the seventh day, when the king was merry with wine, he commanded... the seven eunuchs who attended him to bring queen vashti before the king, wearing the royal crown, in order to to show the people and the officials her beauty; for she was fair to behold. but queen vashti refused to come at the king's command conveyed by the eunuchs. at this the king was enraged, and his anger burned within him." esther 1:10-12; ... queen vashti is someone we don't get to really know through esther's story. we know that she refused the king and therefore was stripped of her royal position. some think that she was probably killed over her decision. many read the book of esther solely with a feminist slant-- which is understandable. i was working on the collages when the #metoo movement first began and when i was questioning my own role in the church. i'm still honestly working through some of that. i live fairly independently and believe strongly in the woman's voice. i agree with @bethmoorelpm that i don't think that you can strip the entire book down to a gender war. as she says, â€œthe conflicts in esther are those caught in the crossfire between wisdom and foolishness, modesty and licentiousness, bravery and cowardice, waiting and acting, living and dying." ... #bookofesther #collage #analogcollage #handcutcollage #papercollage #art #biblejournaling #bibleverses

text:
this world is your best teacher. 
there is a lesson in everything if you have an open mind.
there is a lesson in each experience.
learn it and become wise. 
every failure is a stepping stone to success. 
every difficulty or disappointment is a trial of your faith and strength. 
every unpleasant incident or temptation is a test of your inner strength, morals and ethics.

therefore, nil desperandum.

text: as we close out the year #2018 this video makes a lotta sense. the #pastor says, we are coming to a time (idk #ageofaquarius ?) when your #character, #motive, intent, #heart posture, #plans, schemes, plots have to be #pure or itâ€™ll likely get #exposed. if you donâ€™t #believe in a #god, then #technology ensures that something hovers above u like an all-seeing, all-knowing â€œthingâ€.. we are in the age of an #airsign so that means things that pertain to the #air like the #cameraphone, #drones, hackers, wireless/unseen #communication, social media & etc will be the theme for the next 2000+ years so it means alotta ppl are gonna be exposed as if there is a god-like thing around all the time. is that a good thing because itâ€™ll clearly lead to more morality or is it bad â€˜cus we lose our privacy & solitude? we can see the 2018 events from #rappers like #tekashi69 to ar-ab to ralo & etc, who all acted like #gang #leaders online then got arrested for it but really they are just social media thugs being exposed for not really being who they portrayed to be online (i know itâ€™s confusing), to senators & presidents being exposed for frivolous use of donations to paying off pornstars .....even what we see in our beloved american society, when the image of america being the most â€œcivilized nationâ€ is being exposed because most americans are showing their #truecolors & acting like third world savages who canâ€™t embrace change so they use terroristic acts, election fraud & etc to #influence â€œthe swing of the pendulumâ€ but thatâ€™s #life (1st last, then last 1st) now we even can go across the ocean, to a #saudi prince who acts like a civilized, modern , peace-loving ruler in front of #siliconvalley but has been exposed that behind closed doors heâ€™s actually a sadistic, ruthless killer that loves to watch his victims die .. so itâ€™s clear that 2018 can be described as an odd year, a year where things are commercially tailored to the individual & pplâ€™ve power to voice their opinions (#metoo mvmt, #socialjustice ) but less privacy & less human rights (#corporate greed, net neutrality,invasive laws, worker rights, checks on power eroding)

â­ï¸â€editor zoboi (pride, 2018, etc.) lays out the collectionâ€™s purpose: exploring black interconnectedness, traditions, and identity in terms of how they apply to black teens. given that scope, that most stories are contemporary realistic fiction makes sense (rita williams-garciaâ€™s humorous â€œwhoa!â€ which dips into the waters of speculative fiction, is a notable exception). conversely, the characters are incredibly varied, as are the narrative styles. standouts include the elegant simplicity of jason reynoldsâ€™ â€œthe ingredients,â€ about a group of boys walking home from the swimming pool; leah hendersonâ€™s â€œwarning: color may fade,â€ about an artist afraid to express herself; the immediacy of tracey baptisteâ€™s â€œgravity,â€ about a #metoo moment of self-actualization birthed from violation; renee watsonâ€™s reflection on family in â€œhalf a moonâ€; and the collectionâ€™s namesake, varian johnsonâ€™s â€œblack enough,â€ which highlights the paradigm shift that is getting woke. in these stories, black kids are nerds and geeks, gay and lesbian, first gen and immigrants, outdoorsy and artists, conflicted and confused, grieving and succeeding, thriving and survivingâ€”in short, theyâ€™re fully human. no collection could represent the entire spectrum of blackness, however, the presence of trans, afro-latinx, and physically disabled characters is missed: a clarion call for more authentic black-centric collections.

a breath of fresh air and a sigh of long overdue relief. nuanced and necessary.â€ (kirkus reviews (starred review))#bookstagram #booklove #comingup #ibizoboi #blackbooks #blacklibrary #freeblackwomenslibrary

text:
you tell a boy that to be a man is to not show any emotions but you excuse anger. you discourage a boy from seeking help and tell him that to be a man is to be able to have it all together at all times and then we wonder why a large proportion of men are perpetrators of violence.
_
everywhere we turn, men and boys are perceived as monsters and toxic masculity seems to be a plague we are all so desperate to wipe out when we are the ones who created the monsters. 
_
society mass produce violent boys and men, unconsciously. we ourselves created the culture of power, privilege and entitlement and violence for our boys and men and the earlier we come to terms with that reality, the easier it will be to eradicate violence against women and girls perpetrated by men.
_
we can achieve a peaceful and just world but not without the help of men. let's get men involved in the conversation on violence against women and girls! 
@uksaysnomore @unitednations @unwomen @acalltomen @heforshe @timesupnow @projectconsent 
_

text:
â€œi write to listen. i write out of silence. i write to soothe the voices shouting inside me, outside me, all around me. i write because i believe in words. i write because it is a dance with paradox. i write knowing i can be killed by own words, stabbed by syntax, crucified by understanding and misunderstanding. i write past the embarrassment of exposure. i trust nothing especially myself and slide head first into the familiar abyss of doubt and humiliation and threaten to push the delete button on my way down, or madly erase each line, pick up the paper and rip it into shreds â€” and then i realize it doesnâ€™t matter, words are always a gamble, words are splinters from cut glass. i write because it is dangerous, a bloody risk, like love, to form the words, to say the words, to touch the source, to be touched, to reveal how vulnerable we are, how transient. i write as though i am whispering in the ear of the one i love.â€ ~ terry tempest williams ~

text:
when you think of farmers and farming, do you think of science and technology?â €
â €
there's a reason why agricultural degrees are called bachelor of agricultural science degrees... because farming is science based and today's farming is reliant on technology.â €
â €
i'm very proud to have a bachelor of science degree but i'm even more proud of the way simply rose petals has used science to produce the most cutting edge rose petals and edible flowers in the world.â €
â €
our freeze driers are technical and scientific and i used every ounce of my scientific knowledge to develop a technique that produces the highest quality freeze dried flowers in the world.â €
â €
my mother is pictured here with one of our smaller freeze driers. every day a whole host of data is recorded for every single freeze drier and then analysed by mum to ensure their smooth operation.â €
â €
like every successful farmer today, my mother and i have had to take a scientific and technological approach to farming. â €
â €
mum operates our freeze driers with such precision that she will even notice the slightest change in data well before any problem has been discovered. â €
â €
many people doubted that mum and i had the mechanical or technological expertise to operate such heavy machinery, especially in a rural area with limited support. â €
â €
i'm here to tell you that you can do whatever you put your mind to - male or female. mum and i are living proof that female farmers are capable, scientific and tech savvy.â €
â €
we are precise. â €
we are detailed. â €
we produce world class product. â €
we are the 2018 winner of the victorian regional award for agricultural innovation.â €
â €

text:
frida kahlo was a really amazing woman. the story of her life and her way of expressing herself in art made her a myth, but what i admire most about her is the way in which she created her own character little by little. his folkloric clothes, his stone necklaces, his plants and his pets that surrounded him in his little house full of mud basins. it was all part of that character she portrayed and who had real life in her own life. she was the creator of herself. lying on her bed looking at herself in the mirror suffering pain but surrounded by paintings and colors, she got to be known all over the world and fill every place on the planet with her image and be an icon of fashion nowadays. i needed to think about her and understand her work and the best way to do it was to give her life in my own home, with my own hands, and at least if not forever, to have her with me and receive a little bit of her light. she is in barcelona in a place where every day shines with her presence.
.

text:
no te confundas.
no es "feminismo", la otra cara de la misma moneda...
no es querer generar mas separaciÃ³n y distancia entre gÃ©neros...
no es violencia encubierta, ahora hacia los hombres,
ni creernos "mas o mejores" que ellos, 
ni cerrarles la puerta...
no es falta de amor, integraciÃ³n o confianza,
no es querer negarlos o hacer juicios que condenan.

no nos estamos revelando a su fuerza, 
a su masculinidad, a su esencia...
no te confundas.

es el grito ancestral que nos habita
que hoy  pega su alarido.
son cientos y miles de aÃ±os de violencia incrustada,
de callarnos, de bajar la mirada y apretar los dientes.

es la informaciÃ³n de miles de aÃ±os, 
grabada en nuestras cÃ©lulas,
la que esta aullando como una loca.
son todas nuestras abuelas ancestras caminÃ¡ndonos la piel.
humilladas, negadas, abusadas, avergonzadas, quemadas, golpeadas, torturadas, violadas, mutiladas, encerradas, 
calladas, sometidas al silencio del poder masculino, 
por siglos.

no te confundas. 
no soy yo, mujer, ni ella, mujer... es el alarido de todas ellas juntas que nos habitan y nos mueven.
y dicen basta. 
nos hemos despertado 
del tiempo de la sumisiÃ³n y el silencio,
de las lagrimas y el golpe
de presuponer invisibles nuestras emociones.

sentimos. 
y estamos vivas.

no te confundas.
no es un movimiento feminista el que esta tomando voz y forma,
son nuestras miles de abuelas que estÃ¡n vivas
caminando las calles, hablando en los medios,
buscando sanar, ser escuchadas, perdonar, 
desanclar tantos siglos de dolor enterrado en el cuerpo,
y en el alma...
gritan desde nuestro propio holograma interno
polinizan nuestros discursos y miradas.

por fin, hablan.

somos todas todo. 
pasado presente y futuro.
somos la voz de las sinvoz. 
y nuestro andar recupera todos los pasos enterrados. ( eva )

text: i think we lie to ourselves that we believe who we are due to the social expectations placed around us. we contort ourselves to what people wish to believe we are, we attempt to control our persona, we live the lie people wish of us....yet we struggle. the pain of what we are surrounds us. each day it is inescapable. two halves must make a whole. our true selves can be left, right, and halves of each. both do make a whole...in time. if we donâ€™t except ourselves for who we are (and we should) or what we have faced, we can never live for ourselves. if we donâ€™t love ourselves we can never truly love another. regardless of the path that may or may not lay ahead, i donâ€™t wish to be anything but myself. i wonâ€™t let my life be what others want anymore. i can not. i will not. no more. rape should end and no spouse is property. #nomore #metoo #metoomovement #livingagain #living #lifequotes #lifelivedbeautifully #beautifulwomen #lgbtqia #endrapeculture

text:
what are jesusâ€™ issues and concerns?

i think that jesus would be mainly concerned and would dislike, not people, but actions of violence, hate, and discrimination, especially towards children. for example, police brutality is something that crosses racial discrimination and violence, which are two things that jesus wouldnâ€™t like, as his love for his brothers and sisters is strong. also, immigration laws, as they prevent other humans, who we should love instead of hate, from living a life of peace in a better place. jesus would focus on advocating for people who are being mistreated or taken advantage of, such as victims of the #metoo movement, as well as gender inequality, racial inequality, people subject to sex trafficking, etc. he also, shown in multiple scripture passages, has a soft spot for children, and would probably be sad that, nowadays, fewer and fewer children being pulled into knowledge of him and god, so maybe he would be like a large scale missionary? he would want to give all children, but especially mistreated children, equity, happiness, education, opportunities, and more.

text: dear sahm...hi there, iâ€™m a working mom. and, from what i can see, we are more alike than different. but when i see facebook and instagram posts, it feels like itâ€™s all turning into a competition of who is working harder or who has a tougher time...but why? i think motherhood is a team sport, and we need each other. we need to understand each other, and see things in different perspectives. so with that, i want you to know a few things from my perspective. first, i do not believe that you do nothing all day, you work your ass off to take care of your child/children every day - most of the time you do this alone. not only that but you probably are trying to get a million other things done too. i admire you for your patience and for handling every single thing! next, work is not a break for us working moms. we have deadlines, bosses, coworkers, clients, and most of the time no lunch break...when we get that dreaded call, â€œyour daughter/son is sick they need to be picked up...â€ we have to drop everything we are doing and rush home. this call is a constant fear especially when in the middle of stressful situations at work. also, i donâ€™t know if you know this, but i donâ€™t just want your friendship...i need it! i see so many posts on facebook and instagram about moms group events, and meet ups with other moms and babies and i in a way feel envious of the friendships building around me as i canâ€™t make any of those during the week. that tribe everyone has, itâ€™s harder to find and build as a working mom. donâ€™t think i donâ€™t want to be there, because more often then not i wish i could just skip work and be there just like everyone else. lastly, donâ€™t listen to the posts out there..i did not choose my career over spending time with my child. unfortunately, this hurts the most, nobody accuses significant others of this.. i work because i love what i do, and i am able to contribute to our finances. but i am also part of the women in the work place who push for equal pay for women, maternity benefits, etc. i want my daughter to have it better when/if she decides to begin a career in the future - this goes for your daughter too. so sahm you see, letâ€™s do this together. â¤ï¸

text:
trigger warning: sexual assault

last week i ran into a rapist at target.

he isn't my story. he's someone else's but he's a rapist all the same.

i went to get coffee and my phone took a shit. i strolled to the back of the store to see if maybe the tech dept could help.

he was stocking some shit. he looked up and smiled at me, face full of recognition.

i didn't recognize him and i felt my face do that thing it does when i seriously fucking confused. i kept walking.

it wasn't until i caught how short his name was on his nametag and the letter a that my brain lit up. bright red letters: rapist.

i told my bf and he checked to try and ease my worry. we looked him up on fb and sure enough there he was.

he lives in our city. he works at target.

it took 3 days for me to realize the gravity of the trigger.

bc although he isn't my story. he is living the same consequence free life that my abuser is living.

his victims didn't feel comfortable reporting and i understand that. bc i did and it didn't fucking matter.

he gets to walk around like he didn't hurt anyone. like he didn't steal my childhood from me. like he doesn't still darken the corners of my dreams sometimes.

i will rise. and i will take back the small amount of discomfort seeing him shook loose. bc he doesn't deserve that power. i acknowledge the validity of the feeling and i release that shit.

you are not alone. we are not alone. i believe survivors and i hold space for you in whatever part of your journey you're in right now.

#metoo
.
.
.

text: â€œthis past year we have been experiencing a strong backlash from the cis- male students in the @safeteen programs in schools. they claim they are afraid of being falsely accused of sexual assault. we know that only 2-7% of reported assaults are false and that no one lies about rape any more than about any other crime...(fbi) and yet the idea that females will accuse males out of revenge or malice persists. given how incredibly hard it is to get a conviction and the horror show women have to go through in the process, it boggles the mind that people think women would do this on a whim. the #metoo movement has helped women find their voices and speak the truth about what is, and has been for millennia, an epidemic of violence against women. if males are concerned they need to be vigilant about getting enthusiastic consent. as they should be, as they always should have been. when guys say they are getting mixed messages perhaps they could be encouraged to read this as a â€œnoâ€. or at least as a moment to ask whatâ€™s going on. itâ€™s always bothered me when men say they didnâ€™t know..or couldnâ€™t tell that a woman wasnâ€™t fully on board. after all, even a dog can tell when someone is anxious. when a person is raped, they are in a kind of prison and for many itâ€™s a life sentence. yes, it is truly horrific for someone to be falsely accused,  but it is it more horrific than being raped and have no one believe you?  dear good men: if you donâ€™t harm women then relax, this isnâ€™t about you.â€ shared by @safeteen vancouver.  #metoo #webelieveher #consent #consentissexy #enthusiasticconsent

translation: on 9th december 2018, ngo jeevan arth foundation organized a woman's health camp in chaksu village, jaipur. the camp aimed at spreading awareness regarding women's health in which hundreds of women took part along with men and children.

the main cause of organizing the camp was that the women in the village were not keeping good care of their health. considering menstrual health which was found to be the worst as per the survey, we managed to provide medicines, health check up status sheet and other facilities to these women.

in the camp, when we talked to the women, we found that the women were facing terrible health problems not for some days, but for months and years. the shocking revelation was when we found that these women accepted their deteriorated health to be "okay".
name: Jeevan Arth Foundation (NGO)

translation: on 9th december 2018, ngo jeevan ah foundation organized a woman's health camp in chaksu village, jaipur. the camp aimed at spreading awareness regarding women's health in which hundreds of women took pa along with men and children.

the main cause of organizing the camp was that the women in the village were not keeping good care of their health. considering menstrual health which was found to be the worst as per the survey, we managed to provide medicines, health check up status sheet and other facilities to these women.

in the camp, when we talked to the women, we found that the women were facing terrible health problems not for some days, but for months and years. the shocking revelation was when we found that these women accepted their deteriorated health to be "okay".

text:
19 months and 16 days later, i have finally rid myself of this reminder. .
the last person to sit on this chair was someone who i thought was my friend. someone who i trusted enough to allow to come into my apartment. someone iâ€™ve known for twenty years. someone who i no longer speak to, and i am perfectly okay with that. the last person to sit in this chair was a rapist. mine. .
iâ€™m not sure why, but the whole situation has been weighing on me for the last two months. every time the dogs ripped more stuffing out of the cushion. every time i moved the chair so i could workout. every time i put it back so i could have what appeared to be a livable space. itâ€™s too bad because i was really proud of having real living room furniture again... and for paying for it in cash because, well, dave ramsey. and i was really mad because i owned this furniture for all of two months before i hated it. .
i thought i needed help to move it, but you know that feeling you get when you have a goal and you would do anything to reach it? that was me with this. i had to dig deep, but i picked this stupid chair up and carried it out the door and up the stairs and halfway to the dumpster. (thanks, joel and autumn, for helping me find the physical strength and chris for helping me find the mental strength.) when i couldnâ€™t carry it anymore, i cried in the middle of the parking lot for a minute and just decided to roll it through the snow. (fresh snow, by the way. another like 3-4â€ just fell tonight!) .
today, the chair is gone. there is still one more weight from that night that i canâ€™t get rid of yet. the time will come for that. .
tonight, sitting in my living room, i feel so much lighter. i am one step closer to living my best life despite the obstacles. i promised myself to unhook the ball and chain that has been holding me back, and i think this is a good push forward.

text:
this piece of shit's name is jacob walter anderson. he was indicted on 4 counts of sexual assault, yet won't spend a single day in prison. a plea agreement allowed the former baylor university student to plead no contest to a lesser charge of unlawful restraint. 
if the 24-year-old successfully completes three years of deferred probation and pays a $400 fine, his criminal record will be wiped clean of the charge, and he won't have to register as a sex offender. [what in the actual fuck is going on here????]
"the evidence is incredible. he nearly choked her to death. he raped her violently. he left her passed out in her own vomit -- the rape exam confirmed rape," stated vic feazell, the woman's attorney. 
she (the victim) lambasted the court for accepting the plea agreement.
"i am devastated by your decision to let my rapist jacob walter anderson go free without any punishment," the woman said. "he is now free to roam society, stalk women and no one will know he is a sex offender. jacob anderson and all rapists who get away with their crimes will never be cured, never change. if anything they will be emboldened by their power over women and their ability to escape justice and punishment."
i am choosing not to post any of the specific, extremely troubling allegations in any more detail, as they caused me, an assault survivor, to rage like a mother fucker. 
this piece of shit's name is jacob walter anderson. reminds me of another piece of shit named brock turner. #thetimeforjusticeisnow #stophelpingrapistsbeatthesystem #metoo

text: if your potential 502 boss ever tells you how hot you are, how you'd make a cute couple, or any remarks about your looks in yoga pants, trust me, no job is worth it! i first voiced concerns when the potential employer said they'd hired a female lawyer for the same reason everyone else did, "because she was cute." i said, "you can't say that," which  was met with laughter. when his direction eventually turned to me personally, i immediately spoke up, "do you sexually harass all your female employees, or just me?" that did not go over well and i was "educated" that i was not being sexually harassed, because they "take that kind of thing really seriously." one the perks of owning your own business as a woman: no male boss to kowtow to...most are good. some, not so much. and some deny your complaints of sexual harassment: no woman one wants to believe this is happening to them, it's scary and confusing...your boss or someone thinking about hiring you, most of all, definitely doesn't want you to think they've done anything inappropriate. be strong, you are not alone in the ranks of women who've been mis-treated by potential employers and then told you are the one who needs to lighten up! #metoo #justrunningmymouth

good evening. i hope everyone had a peaceful sunday.

given fb algorithm's, i'll keep reminding everyone that nadia's single, "is it too late," will be released on the 20th of this month. you can pre-save now on spotify as well as purchase the song on itunes, apple music, google music, amazon etc.

the song will touch you on many levels. nadia hopes is it too late will help others in their healing process and open the eyes of many.

we thank you for your support and hope once your hear is it too late, you'll share with your friends and family.

she argued that the trans people being classified so narrowly on their gender is based on prejudice. â€œoutsiders say what i can and cannot do, what i am and what i am not.

tw: 
to a sexual assault survivor, jessica jones was everything. after i saw jessica jones, i thought, that's me! people go through this too! other people are angry, other people can't talk about this, other people can't deal with this on their own! it's not just me! i got professionally diagnosed with ptsd after my assault. i started cbt. i'm not alone anymore. i had a name for what i survived. jessica jones will always be close to my heart in a way no other media can be. representation is so meaningful.

#jessicajones #metoo #marvel #representation

text:
i get this question a lot... "your gx is so tall, how does it handle on-road"? the answer: supringly well. i've put almost 1000 miles on this thing already since getting it back, and as i've gotten more comfortable driving it i've realized that it really is more stable than you'd think. why? well, unsprung weight is the biggest factor. yes, my truck has a lot of lift to fit the 40s, but i also added a ton (almost literally) of weight down low. these sd axles are 800lbs. each. each. and, i've got another 160+ lbs per corner in tires and wheels plus a much wider wheel track.

tl;dr: watch this video
Â·Â·Â·Â·Â·

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult
